  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining the Goal**\n\nI\'m currently focused on defining the project\'s parameters. The request is to create a comprehensive prompt for the timetable module, enabling its replication. I\'m prioritizing exhaustiveness, aiming to capture every function, process, and improvement opportunity. This necessitates a thorough analysis of the existing system and identifying potential gaps.\n\n\n**Re-Evaluating the Request**\n\nI\'ve shifted focus. The user\'s request isn\'t a direct code change but a prompt to generate something. My primary objective is now pinpointing the specific information needed in this prompt, specifically the context on the original request. I will need to refine it, clarifying the prompt\'s purpose. I\'ve re-contextualized the initial prompt; I am now ready to begin work on the next phase.\n\n\n**Detailing the Core Components**\n\nI\'m now outlining the core features and improvements. I\'ve begun enumerating specific aspects for the timetable module, including export functionality and automated notifications, and the ability to handle multi-period blocks, such as labs. My primary aim is to capture all essential features of a mature system. I am focusing on the user\'s need for a robust and scalable timetable system.\n\n\n**Enumerating Specific Features**\n\nI\'m now detailing features such as drag-and-drop interfaces for timetable adjustments, room management capabilities, and a drafting/publishing system to manage schedules. I\'m also including print/export functionality, and optional, modern features like generative auto-scheduling. I will also incorporate technical guidelines, including database schema needs, and access controls via Row-Level Security.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "Here is a comprehensive prompt you can copy and paste into another AI system (or this one) to replicate, build, and improve upon the complete Timetable/Schedule Management module. \n\nIt explicitly outlines the necessary data models, the user interface features, the business logic (like conflict resolution), and includes the missing critical features (like Room management, drag-and-drop, and automated conflict detection) that typically lack in basic implementations.\n\n***\n\n### \360\237\223\213 Copy the prompt below:\n\n```text\nAct as a Senior System Architect and Lead Frontend Engineer. Your task is to design and implement a comprehensive, robust Timetable/Schedule Management module for a School Management System. \n\nThe module must be built using React/Next.js (App Router), Tailwind CSS for styling, and a relational database (like PostgreSQL/Supabase). \n\nPlease plan and provide the code for the complete module based on the following strict requirements, ensuring you address common weaknesses found in standard schedule systems.\n\n### 1. Database Schema & Data Model\nDesign the database schema with constraints to support a flexible scheduling system. Required entities:\n- **`subjects`**: id, name, code, colour_hex\n- **`users` (Teachers)**: id, name, role\n- **`classes` (Cohorts)**: id, name (e.g., \"Grade 10A\"), capacity\n- **`rooms` (New Feature)**: id, name, type (e.g., Lab, Lecture), capacity\n- **`timeslots`**: id, day_of_week, start_time, end_time, is_break (boolean)\n- **`schedule_entries` (Live)**: id, class_id, subject_id, teacher_id, room_id, timeslot_id, academic_term\n- **`schedule_drafts`**: Same structure as `schedule_entries` but acts as a sandbox for admins before publishing the final schedule.\n\n### 2. The Conflict Engine (Critical Business Logic)\nThe backend MUST include a robust validations layer (a \"Conflict Engine\") that runs before any schedule entry is saved. It must detect and block/warn against:\n- **Teacher Overlap**: The same teacher cannot be booked for two different classes at the exact same timeslot.\n- **Class Overlap**: The same class cannot have two separate subjects taught at the same timeslot.\n- **Room Overlap**: A physical room cannot hold two different classes at the same time.\n- **Capacity Limits**: A class size cannot exceed the assigned room\'s capacity.\n\n### 3. Core UI Components & Views\nThe UI should be highly interactive, intuitive, and responsive:\n- **Interactive Grid/Matrix View**: A 2D calendar view. Columns = Days of the week, Rows = Timeslots (or vice versa).\n- **Filtering System**: Users must be able to switch the grid perspective easily:\n  - View by Class (e.g., \"Show me the timetable for Grade 10A\")\n  - View by Teacher (e.g., \"Show me Mr. Smith\'s teaching schedule\")\n  - View by Room (e.g., \"Show me the availability of the Science Lab\")\n- **Drag & Drop Interface**: Admins should be able to drag a subject/teacher block from a sidebar into the grid, or move existing blocks between timeslots seamlessly.\n- **Visual Status Indicators**: Color-code blocks by Subject. Show visual warnings (e.g., a red border or tooltip icon) if the block is violating a constraint (e.g., Teacher Double-Booked).\n\n### 4. Drafting & Publishing Workflow\nDo not modify the live schedule directly. Implement a staging workflow:\n- **Draft Mode**: Admins create a \"Draft\" schedule for an upcoming term. All drag-and-drop and edits happen in the `schedule_drafts` table.\n- **Publish Button**: A one-click action that replaces the current `schedule_entries` with the `schedule_drafts` after running a final system-wide conflict check.\n\n### 5. Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)\n- **Admin HR/Academics**: Full read/write access. Can enter draft mode, edit timeslots, resolve conflicts, and Publish.\n- **Teachers**: Read-only access. The dashboard defaults to \"View by Teacher\" filtered to their own ID.\n- **Students/Parents**: Read-only access. Defaults to \"View by Class\" filtered to the student\'s assigned class.\n\n### 6. Missing Improvements to Implement (Advanced Needs)\n- **Export/Print**: Include a client-side function to export the filtered timetable view as a clean, printable PDF.\n- **Multi-Period Blocks**: Allow a single entry to span consecutive timeslots seamlessly (e.g., a 2-hour Science Lab).\n- **Empty Slot Highlighting**: When an admin selects a Teacher to schedule, visually highlight the timeslots in the grid where that teacher is currently *available*, greying out their occupied slots.\n\n### Execution Plan:\n1. First, provide the SQL schema for the database.\n2. Second, provide the backend API routes/actions that handle the fetching, inserting, and the **Conflict Engine** validation logic.\n3. Third, provide the React components for the Interactive Grid, Drag-and-Drop functionality, and Filtering sidebar.\n```\n\n***\n\n### Why this prompt solves standard system weaknesses:\n1. **The \"Conflict Engine\" Requirement:** Most basic apps just blindly save data to the database, resulting in a teacher being booked in two places at once. This forces the AI to build real validation logic.\n2. **Room Management:** Often forgotten. A timetable without physical room tracking is essentially purely theoretical. \n3. **Drafting System:** Prevents users from breaking the current live schedule while they spend 3 days building the schedule for the upcoming semester.\n4. **Drag & Drop:** Generative AI often defaults to basic, clunky HTML forms for data entry. Forcing it to use Drag & Drop logic ensures you get a modern, usable UI."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 6
      nanos: 123921945
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
