  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Reviewing Architecture Blueprint**\n\nI\'m revisiting the architecture blueprint for the PWA project. Specifically, I\'m focusing on \"Phase 1: Foundation,\" and recalling the critical tasks of swapping next-pwa for @serwist/next, and initializing a wrapper for PowerSync or RxDB to handle data synchronization. These foundational elements are essential for a robust, zero-UI layer.\n\n\n**Planning Weakness Resolution**\n\nI\'m now drafting a detailed plan to address the weaknesses identified in the current system. This involves a three-phase approach targeting local-first synchronization, mobile UX, and push architecture. For the initial phase, I\'m exploring the co-existence of SWR and PowerSync, and I am assessing WebAuthN Passkey scope configuration within Supabase Auth.\n\n\n**Analyzing Current Weaknesses**\n\nI\'m now investigating the school management dashboard\'s current shortcomings, and have identified that standard operations are the first major weakness. Digging deeper, I am analyzing `/SYSTEM_REPLICA_GUIDE.md` for clues on prior identified issues, and am checking for associated error logs or bug reports to understand past problems. I\'m focusing my search on the system documentation and architecture blueprints for related information.\n\n\n**Identifying RLS Vulnerabilities**\n\nI\'ve discovered a potential vulnerability related to Row Level Security (RLS) in several API files. My analysis of `/lib/api/` revealed that many files query Supabase directly, utilizing the anonymous client. This raises concerns because, if RLS is enabled on the associated tables, select calls might fail to return data due to the lack of explicit policies. I will need to audit each of these files and related tables to determine the proper remediation steps.\n\n\n**Uncovering Missing Policies**\n\nI\'ve just realized a critical gap! While `supabase_fix.sql` creates a \"permissive_all\" policy and enables RLS for many tables, it seems some, like `leave_requests` and `payslips`, were missed, leading to the return of zero records. Now I\'m checking if there are other overlooked tables in the system that need this fix, and scanning `supabase_fix.sql` to identify RLS enabled tables.\n\n\n**Examining Permissive Policies**\n\nI\'m now focusing on database policies. I\'m going to determine which tables have permissive policies, specifically those created with `CREATE POLICY`. I\'ll grep for these policies to identify the tables which allow all access. I\'m particularly concerned with `leave_requests` and `payslips` which weren\'t originally configured with a permissive policy and returned zero records when queried via `anon_key`. I\'m now thinking about how server actions with the `SERVICE_ROLE` key provide a local-first pattern for action security, allowing an alternative way to bypass the problem.\n\n\n**Prioritizing Weakness Mitigation**\n\nI\'m now outlining a mitigation strategy focusing on data fetching staleness, RLS access control, and UI error isolation, following up on the system\'s core weaknesses. I\'m prioritizing the SWR cache key staleness/revalidation gaps, because I\'ve realized mutate calls could be missing or failing if not revalidated across SWR hooks, or from RLS policy issues, especially on standard clients. Also, I am going to focus on access control by validating standard users.\n\n\n**Validating API Offline-ability**\n\nI\'m now focusing on improving offline capabilities by enhancing the service worker and ensuring critical API queries are offline-ready. I will ensure lists like payslips, leaves, and the schedule are cached properly, and implement client-side mutated call verification for `leave_requests` and `payslips` lists. I also need to make sure any other table queries have protections if RLS issues occur. I\'ll test the compilation page to certify success. Finally, I will check our SWR calls and mutating functions for `leave_requests` and `payslips`.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I am going to check `/app/layout.tsx` using `view_file` to see how the application wrapper is structured, specifically if there is a Service Worker registration script or SWR global cache wrapper in place. This will allow us to ensure local-first resilience works flawlessly across the entire system."
