  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering Offline Capabilities**\n\nI\'m exploring offline persistence caching, specifically considering SWR\'s capabilities. I\'m thinking about either implementing offline caching directly within SWR or syncing SWR\'s data with IndexedDB/localStorage for instant availability when offline. The latter seems promising.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "An extremely elegant and robust first-phase step towards a true **Local-First, Offline-First PWA** is to integrate **SWR Local Storage / IndexedDB Cache Synchronization** into our global SWR configuration, paired with runtime network caching configuration in Serwist (Service Worker). \n\nThis solves the \"empty list on load\" and \"complete offline failure\" weaknesses of traditional cloud-attached SWR:\n1. **Immediate Hydration**: On boot, SWR will immediately restore its cache from client storage. Lists (leaves, payrolls, classes, etc.) render instantly without waiting for a server roundtrip.\n2. **Offline Resilience**: If the user is fully offline, the stored cache remains visible and interactive.\n3. **Optimistic Updates**: Mutating SWR updates the client state immediately.\n\nHere is our plan for Phase 1.\n\n<plan>\nProblem:\n- Traditional web apps display blank loading skeletons or error messages when offline, or experience query flicker on slow connections. Let\'s establish a fast, elegant local cache using a lightweight Client Cache Provider in SWR, and hook it up to standard service worker rules for dynamic API routes.\n\nApproach:\n1. **Update SWRProvider**: Implement an isomorphic, robust LocalStorage caching provider for client SWR that persists queries across sessions and loads them immediately on startup.\n2. **Optimize server-side action calls**: Ensure default error parameters do not throw global uncaught crashes but fall back to cached datasets cleanly.\n3. **Register Service Worker Client-side**: Make sure next-generation service worker loading registers early inside a client utility to handle push and static/dynamic cache requests on mobile devices.\n4. **Compile/Verify**: Run the linter and compiler to guarantee all dependencies compilation.\n\nArchitecture & Performance Impact:\n- Zero memory degradation. Loads are instant (O(1) read from localStorage). Limits SWR data re-fetches.\n- Error Boundaries are already in place to isolate visual components.\n\nEdge Cases & Security:\n- Avoid persisting sensitive user passwords. SWR handles fetch results, which are standard data payloads.\n- Added environment check to prevent SSR hydration mismatches in Next.js Server Components.\n</plan>\n\n### Step 1: Modifying `/components/swr-provider.tsx` to handle Local-First Caching\n\nLet\'s inspect the `SWRProvider` and write a robust, SSR-safe client-side cache persistence adapter. We will view it and then apply our change.\n\nLet\'s edit `/components/swr-provider.tsx` to add isomorphic LocalStorage persistence. Let\'s prepare the tool call."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 1
      nanos: 723005816
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
